{
  "doc_id": "30011",
  "text": "Recent years have witnessed a steady increase in both theoretical and experimental research on semiconductor lasers (SL) subject to delayed optical feedback (DOF). On the one hand, even very small amounts of feedback can be sufficient to drive the laser into the coherence-collapsed regime [CITATION_1] , which manifests itself by linewidth enhancement by several orders of magnitude and laser chaos [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In applications, finding means to avoid the corresponding deterioration of the beam quality is of crucial importance. From the viewpoint of nonlinear dynamics, however, the wealth of bifurcation phenomena encountered in this regime has been of growing interest ever since the first theoretical investigation in [CITATION_4] , where the plane-wave Lang-Kobayashi model (LK model) was derived (for a review, see [CITATION_5] and the references therein). On the other hand, DOF may be deliberately applied to improve mode selection and to achieve considerable linewidth reduction [CITATION_6] . Moreover, controlling chaos in SL by means of DOF has been demonstrated in a recent theoretical investigation [CITATION_7] .",
